<hr>
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <hr><a name="mealpennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEAL FLAG/PENNANT</dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd2.html#dinnerflag">dinner flag</a>&rsquo;. </dd>
  <dd>2) In US usage the practice, almost certainly obsolete, of flying a red triangular 
  pennant from the port yardarm (or spreader) of a pleasure vessel when the crew are at 
  meals &ndash; a crew&rsquo;s meal pennant (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd2.html#dinnerflag">dinner flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg6.html#guestflag">guest on board flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvo2.html#ownerabsentflag">owner absent flag</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-y.html#yardarm">yardarm</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d526.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d526.gif" alt="Dinner flag" border="0" width="108" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d538.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d538.gif" alt="meal pennant" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em><a href="xf~yct.html#dinner">Dinner Flag</a>, US (fotw); 
  <a href="xf~yct.html#crew">Meal Pennant</a>, US (fotw)</em></p></dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="meatball"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEATBALL </dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battleefficiencypennant">battle efficiency pennant</a>&rsquo;.
  <br>2) In US usage, now obsolete, a colloquial (and possibly derogatory) term for the national 
  roundel of Japan see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr4.html#roundel">roundel 1)</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#hinomaru">hinomaru</a>&rsquo;).<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1130a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d1130a.gif" alt="battle efficiency pennant" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1146.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d1146.gif" alt="Japanese roundel" border="0" height="108"></a><br><em>
  <a href="us^nvawd.html#bate">Battle Efficiency Pennant</a> (fotw); National Roundel of 
  <a href="jp.html#roundel">Japan</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr><a name="median"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEDIAN </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm2.html#meridian">meridian</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1366.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1366.gif" alt="[mdian]" border="0" height="108"></a>

  <hr/><a name="mediated"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEDIATED</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term to dimidiated - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd2.html#dimidiated">dimidiated</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1345a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d1345a.gif" alt="arms - Dobrodzie&#324;, Poland" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1345b.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d1345b.gif" alt="flag - Dobrodzie&#324;, Poland" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
<em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pl-op_do.html">Dobrodzie&#324;</a>, Poland (fotw)</em>
</dd>

  <hr/><a name="medievalsailingship"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEDIEVAL SAILING SHIP (or MEDIEVAL SAILING VESSEL) </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#cog">cog</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#nef">nef</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;sailing ship&rsquo;).  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3849.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d3849.gif" alt="medieval sailing ship" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3849a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d3849a.gif" alt="medieval sailing ship" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
<em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pl-wm-el.html">Elbl&#261;g County</a>, Poland (fotw)</em>
</dd>
  
  <hr><a name="membered"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEMBERED</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term used when the legs of a bird are of a different tincture from that of its 
  body (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva6.html#armed">armed 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva6.html#armedandlangued">armed and langued</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva8.html#attired">attired</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb4.html#beaked">beaked</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#langued">langued</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tincture</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
<a href="../images/v/vxt-d778b.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d778b.gif" alt="Neuch&acirc;tel, Switzerland" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d778a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d778a.gif" alt="arms - Biale Blota, Poland" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1721.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d1721.gif" alt="Doppleschwand, Switzerland" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br><em>Flag of
  <a href="ch-ne033.html">Neuch&acirc;tel</a>, Switzerland (fotw); 
  Arms of <a href="pl-kp-bb.html">Bia&#322;e B&#322;ota</a>, Poland (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="ch-lu001.html">Doppleschwand</a>, Switzerland (fotw)</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr><a name="memorialflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MEMORIAL FLAG</dt>
  <dd>1) In largely (but not exclusively) US usage, a small national flag (affixed to a short staff) 
  which, on specified memorial occasions, is implanted on the graves at military cemeteries &ndash; a 
  grave decoration flag.</dd>
  <dd>2) A flag designed to memorialize one or more persons, or to express sympathy for people in a 
  specific situation. Such flags may or may not be officially recognized, and are sometimes created 
  by adding symbols or wording to a national or other recognized flag (see also �<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#celebratory">celebratory flag</a>� and �<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#commerorativeflag">commerorative flag</a>�).</dd>
  <dd>3) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#commerorativeflag">commerorative flag</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d647.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d647.gif" alt="POW-MIA flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1584.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1584.gif" alt="9/11 memorial flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d647b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d647b.gif" alt="9/11 memorial flag" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
  <a href="us^pow.html"><em>POW-MIA</em></a><em> Flag, US and Canada (fotw) </em> 
  <a href="us-911.html"><em>9/11 Memorial</em></a><em> Flags, US (fotw)</em></p></dd>
  <hr><a name="menorah"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MENORAH </dt>
  <dd>A seven-branch candlestick symbolic of Judaism, that is featured on the 
  national arms and the Presidential Standards of Israel, together with other flags 
  both past and present (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-m.html#magendavid">Magen David</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp6.html#presidentialstandard">presidential standard</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  &nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d596.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d596.gif" alt="[Presidential standard - Israel]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d596a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d596a.gif" alt="[Arms of Israel]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4472.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4472.gif" alt="[menorah]" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
  <em><a href="il^presi.html">Presidential Standard</a> and
  <a href="il.html#coa">National Arms</a>, Israel (fotw);
  Flag of the <a href="il_nii.html">National Insurance Institute</a>, Israel (fotw)</em></p>
  </dd>
 
  <hr><a name="merchantpennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERCHANT ENSIGN </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;civil ensign&rsquo; under &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d2582.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2582.gif" alt="[Merchant ensign]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4046.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4046.gif" alt="[Merchant ensign]" border="0" height="108"></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4047.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4047.gif" alt="[Merchant ensign]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em>Merchant/<a href="hr~.html">Civil Ensign of Croatia</a> (fotw); Merchant/<a href="ch-sea.html">Civil Ensign of 
  Switzerland</a> (fotw); Merchant/<a href="in~.html#civ">Civil Ensign of India</a> (fotw)</em>
  
  <hr><a name="merchantflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERCHANT FLAG </dt>
  <dd>An alternative term, now obsolete, for the civil ensign -see &lsquo;civil 
  ensign&rsquo; under &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#theensign">ensign, the</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d587.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d587.gif" alt="[Merchant flag]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2551.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2551.gif" alt="[Merchant flag]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2552.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2552.gif" alt="[Merchant flag]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em>Merchant Flag of <a href="es1785~c.html">Spain</a> 1785 &ndash; 1927 (fotw);
  Merchant Flag of <a href="it-luc-d.html#mer18">Lucca</a> 1818 � 1819 (fotw); 
  Merchant Flag of <a href="me_k.html#civ">Montenegro</a> 1880 - 1918 (fotw) </em></p></dd>
  <hr><a name="merchantjack"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERCHANT JACK </dt>
  <dd>An alternative term, now obsolete, for the civil jack (see &lsquo;civil 
  jack&rsquo; under &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-j.html#jack">jack</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d2553.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2553.gif" alt="[merchant jack example]" border="0" height="107" width="174"></a>&nbsp; <a href="../images/v/vxt-d918.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d918.gif" alt="[merchant jack example]" border="0" height="107" width="174"></a>&nbsp; <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2554.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2554.gif" alt="[merchant jack example]" border="0" height="107" width="174"></a><br>
  <em>Merchant Jack of <a href="gb-eng.html">England</a>/UK 1674 � 1824 (fotw); 
  Merchant Jack of the <a href="gb-rac.html">Royal Africa Co.</a>, England/UK 1672 &ndash; 1752 (fotw);
  Merchant Jack of the <a href="gb-eic.html#flag">Honourable East India Co</a>, England/UK c1660 � 1863 (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr><a name="merchantmark"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERCHANT MARK</dt>
  <dd>In English heraldic usage the term, now obsolete, for the symbol of either identity or profession used by the non-armigerous � but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh6.html#housemark">house mark</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva6.html#armigerous">armigerous</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d2049.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2049.gif" alt="[merchant mark example]" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
  <em>(Parker)</em></dd>
  
  <hr><a name="merchantpendant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERCHANT PENNANT (or PENDANT)</dt>
  <dd>1. In Belgian usage (although rarely employed), a variant of the naval masthead pennant officially authorized for merchant vessels - see �<a href="#mastheadpennant">masthead pennant</a>� (also 
  �<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#streamer">streamer 2)</a>�).
  <br>
  2. In Habsburg Imperial usage, now obsolete, a term that may be used for the masthead 
  pennant when flown from a merchant vessel between 1786 and 1804, and identical to that 
  flown by contemporary and later warships - see 
  &lsquo;<a href="#mastheadpennant">masthead pennant</a>&rsquo; (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pendant">pendant</a>�)<br>3. See �<a href="vxt-dvm2.html#merchantshippendant">merchant ship pendant</a>�   
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d4086.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4086.gif" alt="[Merchant Pendant example]" border="0" height="50"></a><br>
  <em>Merchant Pendant, Belgium (fotw)</em><dd>
	<p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1018.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1018.gif" alt="[Merchant Pendant example]" border="0" height="50"></a><br>
  <em>Merchant Pendant, Habsburg Empire 1786 � 1806 (fotw)
  <p>Please note that in European usage, as far as is known, only Belgium and the Habsburg Empire 
  have permitted merchant vessels to legally fly a masthead pennant of this type.</em></dd>
  
  <hr><a name="merchantshippendant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERCHANT SHIP PENDANT (or PENNANT)</dt>
  <dd>A term for those masthead pennants, now obsolete, that were flown by Brazilian 
  merchant vessels in the 19th Century to show in which province they were registered � a galhardete 
  � but see &lsquo;registration flags� and �<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#galhardete">galhardete 2)</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pendant">pendant</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant 2)</a>&rsquo;).&nbsp;   
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1019a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1019a.gif" alt="[Merchant Ship Pendant example]" border="0" height="50" width="300"></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1019b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1019b.gif" alt="[Merchant Ship Pendant example]" border="0" height="50" width="300"></a><br>
  <em>Merchant Ship Pendants:  <a href="br-pe.html#merc">Rio Grande do Sul</a> and 
  <a href="br-pe.html#merc">Pernambuco</a>, Brazil (fotw.</em></dd>
  
  <hr><a name="meridian"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERIDIAN </dt>
  <dd>An imaginary line drawn (either vertically or horizontally) through the centre 
  of a flag &ndash; the median - a vertical or horizontal meridian/median. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1366.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1366.gif" alt="[meridian]" border="0" height="108"></a>  
  </dd>
  
  </dd>
  
    <hr><a name="merlette"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERLETTE</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term to martlet - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-m.html#martlet">martlet</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4806.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4806.gif" alt="[merlette]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="gb-e-sxe.html">East Sussex</a>, UK (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
    
  <hr><a name="mermaid"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">MERMAID</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry and vexillology the term used to describe a charge in the form of a mythological creature that is part female and part fish � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#heraldicbeasts">heraldic beasts</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4807.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4807.gif" alt="[mermaid]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4808.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4808.gif" alt="[mermaid]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4809.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4809.gif" alt="[mermaid]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="br-sp223.html">Iaras</a>, Brazil (fotw); 
  Arms of <a href="nl-fr_mm.html#mm)">Makkum</a>, The Netherlands (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="pt-trfag.html#av">Alvarelhos</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <dd>
  <hr><a name="metavexillology"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">META-VEXILLOLOGY</dt>
  <dd>A newly introduced term, and as yet not fully defined, but one that could that be considered 
  to cover the study of flags from an extended, new or varied perspective (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#vexillology">vexillology</a>&rsquo;).
    <dd>
  
  <hr><a name="metals"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">METALS </dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvo2.html#or">or</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva4.html#argent">argent</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1240a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1240a.gif" alt="[argent]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1240b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1240b.gif" alt="[or]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br><em>Argent and Or</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr><a name="meteorflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">METEOR FLAG (or ENSIGN) </dt>
  <dd>In largely (but not exclusively) US usage now obsolete, an alternative term for 
  the British red ensign &ndash; see &lsquo;red ensign 1)&rsquo;.
  <p>
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d270b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d270b.gif" alt="[red ensign]" border="0" height="108"></a><br><em>British 
	<a href="gb-ensr.html">Red Ensign</a> (fotw)</em>
  <p><em>Please note that there is some doubt as to whether, when first coined (in it is 
  suggested 1801), the term &ldquo;British Meteor Flag&rdquo; referred to the red ensign, or to the 
  union jack.  
 </em>  
 </dd>

</dl>
